## 6. Open Problems and Roadmap

The following problems remain open and define the research roadmap.

### 6.1 Trajectory Reconstruction Problem Formalization

The TRP has not yet been formally defined in the computational complexity sense.
A formal definition — analogous to the hardness assumptions underlying RSA or ECDH —
is required to establish IEPP on a rigorous security foundation.

Target formulation:

> Given R₁...Rₙ and C₁...Cₙ, no probabilistic polynomial-time algorithm
> can produce Rₙ₊₁ with probability non-negligibly greater than random.

### 6.2 Clone Detection via Trajectory Statistics

Current Layer 3 metrics do not sufficiently separate original from cloned trajectories
(gap: 0.015). Candidate approaches under investigation:

- Lag-1 and lag-2 autocorrelation of norm sequences
- Velocity and acceleration of state norm progression
- Cross-trajectory divergence rate measurement

Results from v0.4 experiments will be reported in the next whitepaper update.

### 6.3 Entropy Source Minimum Conditions

The minimum entropy source requirements for IEPP security guarantees
have not yet been formally specified.
Current implementations use OS-level randomness (os.urandom),
but the conditions under which weaker entropy sources remain sufficient are undefined.

### 6.4 Hardware Integration Path

Defense against Level 3 adversaries requires hardware-anchored entropy.
Integration paths with TPM 2.0 and hardware PUF architectures are under consideration.

